name: Buckeye
description: sometimes a small bush, sometimes a small tree. Buckeye blooms appear in 4 to 12 inch plumes at the tips of the branches in spring to early summer. Their colors range from the white of horse chestnut, bottlebrush and California buckeye blooms, to the yellow of Ohio buckeye, to the hummingbird-attracting scarlet of red buckeye. Its leaves bud in late winter/early spring and fall off midsummer, taking advantage of the coolest, wettest part of the season (smartest tree in CA).
location: one the Wild Places hike, Cresta Blanca hike where single track split off from the fire road
coolFact: “eyed” seeds once carried by children as good luck charms.Sometimes called the California Christmas Tree because the buckeye look like ornaments.The raw seed is poisonous, do not eat it!

name: Miner’s Lettuce
description: Rosette-forming plant, growing to a maximum of 40cm in height, the small pink orwhite flowershave five petals which grow at the end of the stems. It is common in the spring, and it prefers cool, damp conditions. It first appears in sunlit areas after the first heavy rains. Though, the best stands are found in shaded areas, especially in the uplands, into the early summer. As the days get hotter, the leaves turn a deep red color as they dry out.
location: along the path that leads down to the lower parking lot; Wild Places hike; near stair for climbing wall.
coolFact: The common name miner's lettuce refers to its use by California Gold Rush miners who ate it to get their vitamin C to prevent scurvy.Mild tasting leaves are not unlike spinach in texture
